The `for` loop here will always return on the first iteration (`Path.cwd()`), meaning `skills_dir.parent` is never checked. If the intention is to use the first one that exists, you should add an `.exists()` check. If the intention is just to fallback, the loop isn't doing what's intended.

```python
def _default_database_url(skills_dir: Path) -> str:
    for base in (Path.cwd(), skills_dir.parent):
        db_path = base / DEFAULT_DATABASE_FILENAME
        if db_path.exists():
            return f"sqlite:///{db_path.resolve()}"
    return f"sqlite:///{(skills_dir.parent / DEFAULT_DATABASE_FILENAME).resolve()}"
```

Any errors from `patchFeedback` will be silently swallowed here. It might be worth adding a `catch` block to at least log the error or show a simple alert so the user knows their save failed.

```typescript
  async function handleSave() {
    setSaving(true);
    try {
      await patchFeedback(item.id, {
        status,
        resolution_url: resolutionUrl.trim() || null,
      });
      onUpdated();
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Failed to save feedback triage state:', err);
      alert('Failed to save changes. Please try again.');
    } finally {
      setSaving(false);
    }
  }
```
